{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_egypt_ver02/data/sn83030214/0017503934A/1908050201/0016.xml":{"full_text":"ROADS LIABLE TO FINE\nTHE COMMODITY CLAUSE.\nTook Effect Yesterday\u2014 Resolution\nto Suspend It Discussed.\nROADS LIABLE TO FINE\nTHE COMMODITY CLAUSE.\nTook Effect Yesterday\u2014 Resolution\nto Suspend It Discussed.\n{From The Tribune Bureau.)\nWashington. May 1.\u2014The Senate spent the\ngreater part of to-day\u2019s session debating the Elkins\nresolution suspending for twenty months the com\nmodity clause of the railroad rate law. The im\npracticability of passing this resolution was de\ncided on by the leaders some time ago, but Sen\nator *Elkins was so confident that he could obtain\nthe approval of tne resolution that it was per\nmitted to come up to-day on a vote. Mr. Elkins,\nwho apparently supposed he would encounter no\nserious difficulty once the resolution was seriously\ntaken up, asked that it Le read in order that it\nmight be perfected, and then the floodgates of\noratory and legislative amenament were opened.\nSenator Fulton offered his bill conferring on the\nInterstate Commerce Commission authority to pass\non all proposed increases of freight rates before\nthey go into effect as an amendment. This caused\nconsiderable debate, and then Senator Heyburn\noffered his resolution, which seeks to enforce what\nis known as \u2018\u201c\u2018the long and short haul clause.\u201d\nSenator Culberson oroposed his car shortage bill\nas an amendment, and Senator Foraker gave no\ntice of a substitute tor the Elkins resolution which\nhe intends to offer. Before any vote was reached\nit had been proposed to repeal! and re-enact the\nentire fourth and sixth sections of the interstate\ncommerce act, and there is still more to follow.\nThe leaders regard to-day\u2019's debate as demonstrat\ning the accuracy of their contention that any effort\nto amend this law will cause an almost intermin\nable debate and is more than likely to result in an\neffort to reframe the law. They do not expect\nthat final action on the Elkins resolution will be\nreached at this session, but they are glad the de\nhate occurred, as it demonstrates how impossible\nir would be to enact the Hepburn Civie Federation\nbill, which would meet with a similar fate in the\nSenate.\n\nThe commodity clause went into effect to-day, and\nrailroads, therefore, which haul in interstate com\nmerce products of mines or manufactories in\nwhich the carriers are interested are liable to maxi\nmum fines of \u00a35.00 for cach offence. The Elkins\nresolution gives the railroads twenty months addi\ntiona! in which to divorce themselves from these\nproperties, on the ground that the financial condi\ntion of the country has been such that the rail\nroads have been unable to find buyers and to settle\nsuch questions o\u00ae joint ownership as are involved\nin mortgages covering both the railroad property\nard mining or manufacturing property.\n\nWhen the Elkins resolution was called up several\ndays ag\u00bb it went over under objection from Mr.\nCulberson, the Democratic leader. but it was taken\nup to-day by vote of the Senate. Mr. Culberson\nhad refused unanimous consent, and he was first\nrecognized to speak against the resolution. He\nsaid that the committee had given no reasons why\nthe extension should be made, and he called on\nChairman Elkins for an explanation.\nMr Elkins answered that tha condition of the\ncountry demands a delay in the operation of the\nlaw and that the railroads have been unable to find\ncapitalists to take over the coal lands owned by\nthem. For this situation he blamed the recent\npanic, and he said that had it not been for the\nrioney shortage and business depression the rail\nroads would have heen able to comply with the\nlaw. He called attention to the fact that his reso\nlution did not repeal the clause, but only suspended\nit. The Lackawanna and the Reading railroads\nwere especially chartered by the states to own coal\nlands, he said, and he showed that the properties\nwere mortgaged and remortgaged, and that diffi\nculty had been experienced in separating these ob\nligations. Other railroads owning coal lands were\nin the same position, he declared.\nMr Nelson said 1t appeared that the attitude of\nthe railroads was against compliance with the law\nand to litigate as to the power of Congress to enact\nsuch legislation. He expressed the opinion that the\nrailroads were not entitled to any special considera\nticn. 80 long as they undertook to. .attack the\nvalidity of the law, he declared, Congress was\nunder no obligation to favor them.\nMr. McCumber construed the commodity \u201clause\nas not preventing the railroads from owning coal\nmines, mining tlie coal or selling the product of\nthe mines. He said tne coal could be sold at the\nmine to independent dealers, who could ship it\nover the railroad wherever thev pleased, and there\nwould be no violation of the law.\nMr. Warren said that such a transaction would\nbe a perfectly patent evasion of the law.\nMr McCumber admitted that a deal of this char\nacter might be open to suspicion, but he believed\nthere would be no technical violation of the law.\nSenator Elkins was permitted to perfect his reso\nlution in accordance with recommendations from\nthe committee and the Interstate Commerce (om\nmission.\nMr. Fulten then offered his amendment requiring\nthe railroads to keep on file all schedules, including\nJoint rates. Mr. Foraker previously had introduced\nan amendment which provided that the commodity\nclause should not appiy to railreads hauling prod\nucts of mines or manufactures which were owned\nby the railroads at the time the law was passed.\nMr. Hevburn offered his amendment providing that\nrailroads shall not charge a greater tariff for a\nshort haul than for a long haul. He said that the\nevile which have grown up under the diserimina\ntions have attracted the attention of the country,\nand unless they are heeded legislators would hear\nfrom them at the next election.\nAll the amendments were ordered printed, and the\nresolution went over\nSenator Carter gave notice that he would address\nthe Senate in support of his postal savings bank\nbill on Thursday, and Senator (Gallinger obtained\nanimous consent for consideration of and a vote\nis child labor bill for the District of Columbia\nbefore adjournment cn Wednesday,\n[From The Tribune Bureau.\n[From The Tribune Bureau.\nWashington, May 1.\u2014When the conferrees on the\nnaval appropriation bill meet, the House members\nwill agree to the Senate amendment authorizing\nthe immediate appropriation for the two new bat\ntieghips, and the only important point of differ\nence between them will be the question of the pay\nof the navy. The House conferrees will insist on\nsubstituting the Foss bill for the Senate provision\nwhiclr grants an increase of substantially 20 per\ncent for the officers and 10 per cent for the men.\nThe Foss bill equalizes the pay of the army and\nnavy, giving to the officers and men of the navy\nthe same pay given to those of corresponding rank\nin the other arm of the service.\nBUILDING FOR PARIS EMBASSY.\nWashington, May 1.\u2014The Senate Committee on\nAppropriations to-day took the first step looking to\nthe acquisition of property for the American Em\nbassy at Paris by inserting an amendment in the\ndiplomatic and consular bill appropriating $400,000\nfor the purchase of a site and the erection of a\nhuldding for the use of the embassy in that city.\nW. R. WHEELER NOMINATED.\nWashington, May 1.\u2014The President sent to the\nSenate to-day the nomination of William BR.\nWheeler, of California. to be Assistant Secretary\nof Commerce and labor.\nSee Washington\nTHE HEART OF THE NATION\nTE REE-DAY TOUR\nPennsylvania R. R.\nvia\nMAY 7\nRound.Trip Rate $12.00 or $14.50\nfrem Hew York\nAccording to hotel selected\nCovers necessary cxpenses fcr threes days\nTickets gocd returning for ten days.\nDetailed Itineraries and full information cf\nTicket Agents, or C. STUDDS, E. P. A, 2363\nFifth Aveune, Wew York.\n(From The Tribune Bureau.\nNAVY PAY IN DISPUTE.\nTREASURY'S CONDITION.\n\n\nDeficit for April Reported Nearly\n816.006 000\ni\nWashington, May 1.\u2014The statement of the govern\nment receipts and expenditures for April, 1808,\nshows the total receipts to have been $43,918,221 and\nthe expenditures $53,858 784, leaving a deficit for the\nmonth of nearly $16,000,000. The deficit for the\nten months of the present fiscal year is 251,644,815,\nagainst a surplus for the corresponding period last\nyear of $56,475,751. The statement shows that in the\nlast ten months there has been a falling off in\nreceipts of $41,397,562 and an increase in expendi\ntures of $66,722,804, making a difference in.the con\ndition of the Treasury of $108.120.366. This amount\nis likely to be increased to $125,000,000 by the close\nof the fiscal! year. In April (he receipts from cus\ntoms amounted to $20,562,060, which is a loss as\ncompared with April. 1907, of nearly $7.0%0,000. The\ninternal revenue receipts were $18,585,568, a loss of\n$2,648,000. The miscellaneous receipts were $4771,\n691. which is a slight gain. The civil and miscella\nneous expenditures amounted to $15,688,281, an in\ncrease of 34,750,000. War Department expenditures\nwere $5,069,832, an increase of $1,020,000. Navy De\npartment expenditures were $11,536,291, an increase\nof 33,480,000. Pensions also showed an increase of\n$1.200,000.\n\n\ni\ni\n\n\n\nThe monthly circulation statement shows the\ntotal circulation of national bank notes on April\n30, 190%, to have been $697,645,688, which is an in\ncrease for the year of $97,731,857 und an increase for\nthe month of $1,238,342. The circulation based on\nUnited States bonds amounted to $62,425,375, an in\ncrease for the year of $75,220,504 and a decrease for\nthe month of $3,408,961. The circulation secured by\nlawful money aggregated $72,220,323, an increase\nfor the year of $49,708,068 and an increase for the\nmonth of $4,647,304. The amount of bonds on de\nposit to secure circulating notes was $628,839,430, and\nto secure public deposits, $226.543.240.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTHE PAPER INQUIRY.\n\nMedill McCormick a Witness\u2014John\nNorris Heard Aeain.\ni\nyvwasnington, May lL\u2014Testifying to-day before the\nwood pulp and paper investigating committee,\nMedill McCormick, publisher of \u201cThe Chicago Trib\nune,\u201d explained his paper contracts for the last\nten years, and said that, although he had a five\nYear contract, with one year yet to run, with the\nInternational Paper Company, the price had been\nraised from $18 to $220 a hundred pounds. His\npurchases, he said, amount to fourteen or fifteen\nthousand tons a year. No one, he said, had ap\nproached him regarding his paper supply for next\nYear. Replying to a question by Mr. Stafford, Mr.\n\u2018McCormick said that so far as his Knowledge went\n\u201cThe Chicago Record-Herald\u201d and \u201cThe News\"\nare paying the same price as \u201cThe Tribune.\u201d The\nHearst papers were getting paper -at something\nless than $2. \u2018The Journal\u201d was paying something\nover $230. With the exception of that going to\nthe last named publication, he said, the paper\nwas all supplied by the International company.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nJohn Norris, representing the American News\npaper Publishers\u2019 Association, continued his testi\nmony. While he was on the stand a call of the\nHouse was ordered.\n\n\n\u201cWell,\u201d said Mr. Mang, \u201cyour ally demands our\npresence.\u201d\n\u201cI think,\u201d said Mr. Miller, \u201cyour ally is a little\nafraid we are going to report at this session of\nCongress.\u201d\n\"I am afraid,\u201d remarked Mr. Norris, \u201che has\nno such apprehension.\u201d\n\ni\n\u201cHe is doing his best to hinder it,\u201d\u201d said Mr.\nMann.\n\n\u201cYou claim,\u201d Mr. Mann said, \u2018that the advance\nis in part caused by an artificial combination, that\nthere is an artificial price that it is fostered by\nthe tariff, and you think we ought to recommend a\nremoval of the tariff. \u2018But suppose it should ap\npear tkat the enhancement in price is caused by\nnormal conditions, by the actual increase in cost\nof material or labor, and not by reason of a com\nbination, do you think, then, we ought to recom\nmend a removal of the tariff?\u201d\nMr. Norris answered that this was such an im\npossible hypothesis that he could not give an an\nswer that would clearly state his mind. He said\nthe publishers would substantially rest their whole\nproposition on the assertion that there not only\nwas a combination, but that the prices being\ncharged were without justification. The statements\nof the manufacturers, he said. as to the cost of\nproduction were absolutely untrue.\n\u201cAs I understand it,\u201d Chairman Mann remarked,\n\u201cyou don't think we would be justified in recem\nmending a removal of the tariff if we should be\nlieve in the end that there was no combination ar\ntificially to advance the price, but that the price\nwas due solely to normal and natural conditions?\u201d\nMr. Norris insisted that he had furnished evi\ndence which would justify the committee in mak\ning further inquiries. An adjournment was taken\nuntil 10 o'clock te-morrow morning.\nEXTENDS TIME TO PRODUCE PAPERS.\nA furger extension of four days was granted\ncr iY to Dr. James E. Campbell, secretary of\nthe Dexter Sulphite Pulp and Paper Company,\nand James A. Outterson, president of the De\nGrasse Paper Company. to produce certain books\nand decuments before the federal grand jury\nwhich is investigating the Manila and Fibre Paper\nManufacturers\u2019 Association.\ni\n\nDr. Campbell and Mr. Outterson had told the\njury of their ineffectual efforts to obtain the re\nquired hooks and papers. Judge Lacombe said he\nwould punish them for contempt of court unless\nthey produced them by Friday. They explained\nvesterday, however, that they had sent a cable\nmessage to John H. Parks, secretary of the asso\nciation, who is in Europe, asking for information\nas to the whereabouts of the papers.\n\u201cPROSPERITY MOVEMENT.\nSt. Louis Organization Plans to\nHare National Scone.\nSt. Louis, Mav 1.\u2014A business organization, to be\nknown as \u201cThe National Prosperity Association of\nSt. Louis,\u201d has been formed as the result of a\nconference held by business men during the last\nthree days, and to-night a formal address was\nissued to the business interests of the country. It\nis proposed to extend the ramifications of the asso\nciation throughout the country for the betterment\nof all classes of business. It is stated that the\nassociation has for its object the encouragement of\nthe return of prosperity and uplifting of business\ninterests generally.\nI\nThe officers of the company comprising the ex\necutive committee are: (Chairman, E. CC. Simmons,\nformerly president of the Simmons Hardware Com\npany; vice-chairman, W. K. Bixby, formerly presi\ndent of the American Car and Foundry (Company.\nIn the forma! address issued to-night it is set\nforth that the purposes of the National Prosperity\nAssociation of St. Louis are: \u201cTo keep the dinner\npail full, to keep the oay car going, to keep the\nfactory busy, to Keep workmen employed and main\ntain present wages.\u2019\nChairman Simmons said to-night:\nWe have formed a business organization. having\nfor its object the encouragement of a return of\nprosperity sooner than might otherwise occur\nwithout help. We believe that present conditions\nare exceedingly favorable to this. On all sides\nwe find expressions of favorable sentiments to\nthe effect that further legislation against rail\nreads and large corporations shall cease, that the\nbusiness interests of the country shall be given a\nrest and that the departments of justice may be\nallowed to proceed with thelr work in a quiet\nmanner. It is absolutely essential to the welfare\nof this country that the railroads should again\nprosper, because more than one and a half million\nmen are in the employment of the railroads to\ndav and as many more are dependent on revenues\nfrom railroad investments, hence it is deemed al\nmost impossible that we should return to a full\nmeasure of prosperity unless the railroads partici\nnkte in the same.\nan Simmons said to-night\nWe have formed a business organization, naving\nfor its object the encouragement of a return of\nprosperity sooner than might otherwise occur\nwithout help. We believe that present conditions\nare exceedingly favorable to this. On all sides\nwe find expressions of favorable sentiments to\nthe effect that further legislation against rail\nreads and large corporations shall cease, that the\nhusiness interests of the country shall be given a\nrest and that the departments of justice may be\nallowed to proceed with thelr work in a quiet\nmanner. It is absolutely essential to the welfare\nof this country that the railroads should again\nprosper, because more than one and a half million\nmen are in the employment of the railroads to\ndav and as many more are dependent on revenues\nfrom railroad investments, hence it is deemed al\nmost impossible that we should return to a full\nmeasure of prosperity unless the railroads partici\npate in the same.\nLITTLE HURT BY JUMP TO RIVER.\nAnother man tried to commit suicide Dyojumping\nfrom the Brooklyn Eridge vesterday shortly before\nnoon. He is now in the Hadson Street Hospital\nsuffering only from shock und cubmersion. Ac\ncording to a letter found in iiis clothes, the man's\nname is Manthres Candylales. He was formerly\nenmploved at the Hotel Riceodonna, at Brighton\npeach.\nMrs Ydward Simons, of No. 15 West 26th street,\nsaw Candylairs suddenly twist himself under ihe\nbridge railing Mrs. Simons told a policeman\nwhat she had witnessed When Candylaies saw\nthe policeman coming on run he leaped to the\nriver.\nCundylajes was fished out of the water by the\ncrew of a tug. which was towing cne of the De\npartment of Street Cleaning scows. He was land\ned at the Fulton Market pier and an ambulance\n\n\ncarried L.m away.\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE. SATURDAY. MAY 2. 1908.\n\nJEFF'S MILD LANGUAGE.\nThe Senate Treated to a Few Choice\nSpecimens of It.\nWashington, May 1.\u2014In the Senate to-day Jeff\nDavis, of Arkansas, moved to discharge the\nCommittee en Judiciary from further consideration\nof his bill \u201cfor the suppression of trusts, pools and\ncombinations in trade.\u201d He spoke about two hours,\nreading most of the time from a typewritten state\nment, which he said he had prepared in advance,\n\u201cthat no intemperate language may escape my\nlips on this occasion,\u201d a thing which, he said, he\nhad rever done hefore.\nHe denounced the trusts, commended the Presi\ndent's recent message, spoke of the removal of the\nmotto, \u201cIn God We Trust\u201d from the coins, and\ndeclared that John D. Rockefeller and J. Pierpont\nMorgan should be indicted for treason. He also\npaid his respects to the press.\n\n\u201cLet scavefigers of plutocracy howl!\u201d he shouted:\n\u201ctruth, God's living truth\u2014where are its dolenders?\nMiserable travesties upon noble manhood, post\ngraduates in all arts of slander or defamation, I\nchallenge the subsidized press; the peopie know\nyour designs and spurn your pretences, whether\nunder show of argument or mere subservient\nhypoerisies. Go, damnable imps of pelf and greed,\n1 defy your taunts! Tear to fragments my politi\ncal career if it comport with your execrable will\nStifle and distort my every utterance. Not satis\nfled, if such be your brutal frenzy, lash my poor\nform into insensibility. Then, if it be your further\npleasure, gnaw from my stiffening bones every\nvestige of quivering flesh. Howl in wretched\nbestiality through my own innocent blood as it\ndrips from your flendish visages. Drag then, if\nyou want, what remains into the filth and the\nvermin of your foul dens and burn it upon the\naltar of Baal, or scatter it before the friendly\nwinds of heaven to your betters\u2014the carrion crows\nof the fleld. All that they may do, all and more,\nif there yet be open further depth of infamy to a\npolluted, besotted press. These ready servants of\ngreed, what have they not done or attempted to\nfasten still more securely an autocracy upon Ns?\nIt seems to be their special function not simply\nto pervert truth but to threaten and terrorize pub\nlic men. Dare a Senator align himself with the\npeople?\u201d What? Yes, men, illustrious servants of\nthe people, have lifted honest voices here and else\nwhere against the march of plutocracy, to fall am\nbushed, politically assassinated, and by whom? By\nthe trusts wearing masks. Ah, sir,\u201d newspaper\nmasks. But Mr. President, insignificant as I am,\nif my political career be marked, let them sharpen\ntheir blades, for 1 will be here at the appointed\nhour, and while here only God can stay my voice\nin behalf of organized, united labor and the yeo\nmanry of America.\u201d\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nSenator Davis's style of oratory is thoroughly dis\napproved by Senators of both parties, and they\nbegan leaving the chamber as soon as he took the\nfloor. until there remained only his colleague, Sen\nator Clarke, who is understood to have felt it neces\nsary to remain to see that Mr. Davis did not attack\nhim. and Senators Telier and Gallinger, who were\ncarrving on a quiet conversation. The galleries\nwere half empty, and the press gallery was almost\nentirely so\nMessage to the Japanese Emperor\u2014207\nLives Lost bv Explosion.\nWashington, May 1.\u2014President Roosevelt sent\nhis condolences to-day to the Emperor of Japan\nregarding the blowing up of the Matsushima yes\nterday. The text of the President's message fol\nterday. The text of the Presicenl s message 10i\nlows:\nTo the Emperor of Japan. Tokio.\nThe American people are deeply shocked and\ngrieved at the terrible naval disaster which has\njust caused the loss of the lives of so many gal\nJon: officers and men of the Japanese navy. On\ntheir behalf, and personally on my own account,\n1] desire to express my profound sympathy and\nconcern. and 1 wish it were in my power to show\nthis sympathy in more practical fashion than by\nmere words. THEODORE ROOSEVELT.\nBaron Takahira, the Japanese Ambassador, was\ndeeply touched by the sympathetic tone of the\nPresident's dispatch. He sald:\nWe alwavs very highly appreciate the friendly\nsentiment invariably maintained by the ['nited\nStates government. In such times of distress the\nwords of sympathy from the President of the\nT'nited States will be most gratefully received by\nthe Emperor of Japan and the people at large, and\nundoubtedly this message will have very good effect\nupon the maintenance of the already happy rela\ntions between the two countries\nCommander Dougherty, American naval attach\u00e9\nat Tokio, to-day informed the Navy Department\nthat the total casualties by the explosion were 207\nmen. His dispatch follows:\nTokio. May 1.\nMatsushima was destroved at Pescadores April\n30. Magazine expivsion. Loss 23 officers, 33 mid\nshipmen, one warrant officer and 150 men.\nAVRIL, MLA) 4\u00bb\nMatsushima was destroyed at Pescadores April\n30. Magazine expiusion. Loss 23 officers, 33 mid\nshipmen, one warrant officer and 150 men.\nMANY BODIES IN SUNKEN CRUISER\nTokio, May 1.\u2014An official report from the Jap\nanese cruiser Matsushima, sunk by an explosion in\nharbor of Makang, FPescadores Islands, on\nApril 30, says that the divers have discovered a\nhuge rent on the port side. The afterdeck is shat\ntered, and wreckage in the interior prevents the\nremoval of many bodies. The bodies of the captain\nand commander of the cruiser have been recovered.\nthe\nMR. CHURCHILL AT DUNDEE.\nA\nOpposition Well Organized, but His Election\nRegarded Certain.\n\nDundee, May 1.\u2014Winston Spencer Churchill. pres\nident of the Board of Trade, whose recent failure to\nbe returned to Parliament from the Northwest Di\nvision of Manchester has forced him to seek a\n\u201csafe\u201d seat, arrived here this morning to contest\nthe vacancy caused by the elevation to the peerage\nof Edmund Robertson. 4\nThe president of the Board of Trade has a well\norganized oppesition to fight, but it will require an\nenormous turnover of votes to defeat him. The\nUnionist candidate, Sir George Baxter, has a pow\nerful local influence, and the Labor candidate, G. H.\nStuart, while a novelty in this country, is an out\nand-out prohibitionist. Mr. Scrymgeour, of the\nUnited Irish League, is-urging the Irish voters to\ngive their complete support to Mr. Churchill, on\nthe ground that Premier Asquith has adopted Mr.\nChurchill's pledges at Manchester regarding Home\nRule for Ireland as representing the policy of the\ngovernment,\nEIGHT HUNDRED PERSONS RESCUED.\nThe Steamer Koln Badly Damaged in Col\nlision\u2014A Child Drowned.\nBremen. May 1.\u2014The North German Lioyd\nsteamer Koln, which left here yesterday for Balti\nmore and Galveston, was in collision in a thick fog\nlast evening with the Hamburg tank steamer Em\nperor Nicholas 1I, nine miles off Norderney. The\nEmperor Nichoias II struck the Ko6ln amidship.\nThe steamer Feldmarschall. a German-East African\nliner. responded tc signals and took off 820 pas\nsengers from the K\u00e9ln. One child was drowned in\nthe transfer.\nThe Feldmarschall took the Koln in tow and\nbrought her into Bremerhaven, arriving this morn\ning. The K&ln carried only second class and steer\nage passengers. The Emperor Nicholas 1I had her\nbows stove in and was otherwise badly damaged.\nHer hold is partly filled with water. A tug has\nbeen sent to her assistance.\n\n\u00absir ROBERT HART LEAVES SHANGHAI\nShanghai, May 1.\u20148ir Robert Hart, chief oi the\nmaritime customs service of China, left here to\nday for Europe on a vear's leave of absence. [le\nhas received the highest honors from the (Chinese\ngovernment, and prominent foreign dnd Chinese\nresidents bade him farewell to-day.\nwill ASK MR. LEISHMAN TO EXPLAIN.\nWashington, May lL.\u2014Representative Murcock, of\nKansas, to-day took up with the State Department\nthe alleged action of Ambassador Leishman in en\ndeavoring to induce Mrs, Bernard Warkentin to\nsign a paper releasing the Turkish prince who aec\ncidentally shot her husband on a railroad train\nnear Damascus from prosecution. The State De\npartment will request an explanation of the am\nbassador. No formal complaint against Mr. Leish\nSg ee\nbeen fil\nPriladelphia, May 1.\u2014The body of Frank A. Me\n(;ill, twenty-three years old, of No. $3 Gates ave\nnue. Brooklyn, was found floating in the Delaware\nRiver here to-day McGill had been reported to the\npofice as missing \u2018from his home for several weeks,\nand a brother-in-law was here making laquiries\nwhen the body was found.\nTHE PRESIDENTS SYMPATHY.\neanntkli YN MAN FOUND DEAD.\nCHINA'S TROUBLES GROW.\nView of Fleet's Visit\u2014The. Boycott\nAgainst Japan.\nPeking, May 1.\u2014It is understood here to-day by\nChinese officials that the purpose of the Washing\nton authorities in dividing the American battleship\nfleet into two squadrons is to enable the vessels\nto visit Japan and China simultaneously, and the\nfeeling of disappointment has. in a measure, been\nlessened. The impression prevails among the Chi\nnese, however, that what they call the definite pur\npose of the fieet's presence in Asiatic waters has\nbeen foiled by an attempt to neutralize the pelitical\ninterpretations given to the fleet's movements in\nthe For East, particularly at this time, when\nChina's difficulties are increasing.\nJapan is facing a serious situation as a result\nof the boycott arising from the Tatsu tneident.\nAdmiral Ijuin, of the Japanese navy, whose cruiser\nsquadron is now anchored off Taku, was received\nin audience by the Emperor and Empress Dowager\nto-day. Coincident with this cccurrence Japan is\nseeking the support of Great Britain to put a stop\nto the boycott by joint representations to China.\nThe boycott is spreading, and Japan is not satisfiefid\nwith China's efforts to stop it. The Japanese au\nthorities here attribute the growth of the move\nment to the native press. which is without control\nand has been conducting a campaign to make\nknown generally the Chinese side of the incident.\nThey say that the matter has been misrepresented\nand hold the Viceroy of Canton chiefly responsible\nbecause of the enormous commercial influence of\nthe Cantonese.\n\n\n3\n\ni\n\nThe diplomatic representatives of the powers here\nare of the opinion that organized anti-foreign\nmovements \u2018in China are a common danger, and\nthey recognize that the powers should have checked\nthe Chinese boycott on American goods in 1905.\nThey hold similar views regarding the Chinese\nboycott on Japanese goods, although on account of\nthe policy she has pursued on the mainland Japan\nhas few, if any, sympathizers.\n\n\n\n\nChina, by means of a campaign in the foreign\nand native press, is making an intelligent and con\nsistent effort to bring Western influence to bear on\nJapan, but Japan, it is said here, regards this\ncourse as hostile and connects it with what the\nJapanese call the \u201cAmerican championing ef China's\nirdependence\u2019\u201d and the agitation of Englishmen in\nthe Far East against the Anglo-Japanese alliance.\n\n\nHong Keng, May 1.\u2014It was learned here to-day\nthat the American government has accepted an in\nvitation for the battleship fleet to visit Hong Kong\non its wav around the world.\nNO DISORDER IN EUROPE.\nPeaceful May Day Celebrations in Berlin\nand Madrid\u2014A Few Arrests in Paris.\nBerlin, May 1.\u2014The Socialist May Day demonstra\ntions passed off without disorder, despite the fact\nthat many unemployed took part. Twenty-two\nSocialist mass meetings were organized to-day in\nBerlin and its suburbs\u2014a smaller number than in\nprevious vears. It is estimated that 33,000 persons,\nincluding 2.600 women, refused to work to-day, as\nagainst 42,000 last year and 35.000 in 1506. Most of\nthose absent attended meetings where addresses\nin favor of general suffrage were delivered by\nprominent Socialists.\n\n\n\nOver forty trade unions also organized meet\nings. All of them dispersed without disturbances.\nThe strictest precautions were taken by the author\nities to deal with disorder, the entire police force\nLeing held on duty throughout the day.\n\n\nDispatches from the principal cities in the prov\ninces report that May Day everywhere passed off\nquietly.\n\nParis, May 1.\u2014May Day was observed in Paris\nto-day by large meetings in various quarters of the\ncity. at which orators denounced gre treatment of\nworkmen by the capitalist class, after which\nresolutions in favor of an eight hour law and the\ncontinuation of the social revolution were adopted.\n\nThe authorities forbade the street demonstra\ntions planned for this afternoon in the boulevards,\nthe Place de a Concorde and the Champs Elys\u00e9es.\nThe municipal eavalry kept the crowds moving\nuntil 3 o'clock. There were a number of arrests,\nbut no disorders which caused the intervention of\nthe troops.\nDispatches received here from tisaprovinees. re\nport large meetings and processions in the indus\ntrial cities, but no disorders.\n\nMadrid, May 1.\u2014A procession of eight thousand\nworkmen, representing forty organizations, paraded\nthrough Madrid to-day carrying flags. There was\nno disorder.\nMadrid, May 1.\u2014A procession of eight thousand\nworkmen, representing forty organizations, paraded\nthrough Madrid to-day carrying flags. There was\nno disorder.\nCi REDUCING EXPENSES,\nSantiago de Chili, May 1.\u2014The government to-day\nannounced a reduction in the budget for the next\nfiscal vear of 22,000.00 pesos.\nne NANSEN'S SUCCESSOR AT LONDON.\nChristiania, May 1.\u2014The Cabinet accepted to-day\nthe resignation of Fridtjof Nansen. the Norwegian\nMinister to (Great Britain. Dr. Nansen, who has\ndesired to retire for some time, has consented to\nremain in office until after King Edward, who Is\nnow at Copenhagen, visits Christiania. Dr. *Nansen\nwill be succeeded by J. Irgens, at present seretary\nof the legation in London.\nBP BAIRD NOT SENT TO JAIL.\nParis. May l.--Charles P. Baird. of Philadelphia,\nran down and killed a boy at Neuilly on October 10\nlast. while driving an automobile. He was sen,\ntenced to a month's imprisonment and to pay a\nfii1e of 810. The jail sentence was suspended to-day\nunder the first offenders act, but Mr. Baird's fine\nwas increased to $120.- Mr.\" Baird must also pay\n22 NW damages.\nBODY OF BANK ROBBER FOUND.\nWinnipeg. Manitoba, May l.\u2014 While tracking the\nStephen (Minn.) bank robbers from the south border\nto-day, .a party of United States detectives found a\ncorpse on the prairie eight miles northeast of Ste\nphen. Near by was a smali pile of ashes, indi\ncating that the desperadoes were taking no chances\nof identification. The dead man is belieyed to have\nbeen the robber who was shot and wounded by a\ncitizen on the night of the robbery. One hundred\nmen, armed wit rifles. are hunting for the robbers.\nThree suspected persons were arrested at Emer\nson, Manitoba, yesterday, taken to St. Vincent,\nMinn., and placed in jail.\nFOG DELAYS PASSENGERS ON LINERS.\nQueenstown, May 1.\u2014The White Star Line steam\ner (Cedric. from New York for Liverpool, and the\nsame line's steamer Cymric, Boston for Liverpool,\npassed here at 3 o'clock this morning. Both\u2019 ves\nsels proceeded without having landed passengers or\nmails, owing to the heavy weather prevailing.\n\nThe fog made it impossible for 130 passengers\nwho were awaiting the (funard Line steamer Ca\nronia to embark on that vessel when she passed\nhere early this morning. They will be taken by\nthe Mauretania on Sunday.\nthe. clerk of the. United States District Court as\nfollows:\nPetitions ii. bankruptey were filed yesterday with\nInvoluntary, against Gustav Gomprecht, maker\nof sausages at No. 998% Third avenue, by Max Bar\ntell. Maurice Ettlinger and Hirsch Graf, with\nclaims of \u00a325. A. Edward Glasgow appointed\nreceiver. The liabilities are said to be $11.00.\nInvoluntary, against Emil Rump, No. Zi Pearl\nstreet, by Henry Japp. Herman Pauli and Carl\nRump, whese claims foot up 6.358 64.\nFrederick McLaughlin was appointed receiver of\nthe business of Herts Brothers. Arnold, Constable\nCo.. one of the petiticning creditors, assert that\nthe liabilities of the firm amount to $100,000 and\nthe assets to not mare than \u00a35,000. Transfer of\nmoney and goods is alleged.\nWilliam F. Smith was appointed receiver of\nDaniel Cornell Co., merchant tailors. The stock\nand fixtures of the involuntary bankrupt are stated\nto be worth $2,000.\nGeorge D. Graves was appointed receiver of the\nbusiness of John F. Cambeis, No. 384 West 135th\nstreet.\nThe schedules of Louis Cohen, No. 24 University\nPlace, show labilities of $61.29710 and assets of\n$12,218 50, consisting of stock, $8.00: machinery and\ntools, $2.00: accounts due, 311430, and cxempt\nproperty, $7. Of the liabilities $45.598 10 is unse\ncured. The principal creditors are Joseph 8 Mar\ncus, Delancey and Orchard streets, 12000; A. S\nRosenthal, No. Greene street, 31.429; Union EX\nchange Bank. $1,790, and H. H. Pulaski Co., Neo.\n488 Broadway. $1.33.\nThe schedules of D. A. Brinker show liabilities\nof $7.4208% and assets of 71292 consisting of\nstock, $2.00; moneys due on open accounts, $1,364 92,\n\nand deposit in bank, 83. Eh\nMAY 2. 1908.\nBUSINESS TROUBLES.\nJ\\GH)\nPURITY\nand\nEXCELLENCE\n(FRENCH REPUBLIC PROPERTY)\nNatural Alkaline Water\nUnexcelled for table use.\nStandard cure for Dyspepsia, Stomach\nTroubles and Gout.\nAsk vour Physicicn\nee\nNol Genuine\nwithout the word\nARMY AND NAVY NEWS\nFinal Graduation from Annapolis\nPostponed.\n{From The Tribune Bureau.]\nwasounglon, aKa\nDISCOURAGED MIDSHIPMEN.\u2014The midship\nmen who were graduated from the Naval Academy\nin two advanced sections, in September, 13%, and\nFebruary, 107, and who should be out for final\ngraduation after two years\u2019 service at sea next\n\u2018September and in February, 138, respectively,\nhave learned they are not to be finally\ngraduated until June, 18. along with the\nthird section of the class, \u2018the members of which\nleft the Naval Academy for sea in June 1907. The\ndecision has led to protests from all the members of\nthe two advanced sections on the ground that they\nstudied hard and gained advanced graduation with\nthe understanding\u201d that it would be of some practi\ncal benefit to them. They might just as well have\nlagged along witlr the greater part of the class,\nunless there was some reward in it. The decision\nof the Navy Department is, of course, based on the\nlaw, but it is no less a discouragement to the mid\nshipmen, who are understood to have interested\nscme Senators and Representatives in their cause,\nwith the prospect that there will be remedial legis\nlation. The Navy Department will not oppose any\nproposition which .seeks to give the discontented\nmidshipmen what they desire, because it is appre\nciated that they have a good case. There has not\nbeen anything in a long time which has so stirred up\nthe midshipmen as this decision of the Navy De\npariment against those who made such a good reec\nord at the Naval Academy.\n\nlL\n\n\n\n\nhad\n\nORDERS ISSUED.\u2014The following orders have\nbeen issued:\nARMY.\nBrigadier General FREDERICK FUNSTON, from De\npartment of California, July 1; detailed com\nmandant army service schools. Fort Leavenworth.\nFirst Lieutenants CHARLES IL. FOSTER. GEORGE\nF. JUENEMANN, ERNEST G. BINGHAM. WILL\nIAM A WICKLINE, WILLIAM A. DUNCAN and\nHERBERT GIBNER, assistaat surgeons, to\nPresidio of San Franciseo for examination for\npromotion.\nCaptains HENRY A WEBBER. FREDERICK M.\nHARTSOCK. DOUGLAS F. DUVAL. CLARENCE\nJ. MANLY, 